<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About LG dryer repair</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">LG dryers, FlowSense vent diagnostics, the codes the brand telegraphs honestly.</h2>

    <p>LG is one of the largest dryer brands in our 5-county service area, DLE / DLEX electric dryers in standalone laundry rooms, DLG gas variants in older homes, and LG WashTower vertical stacks in newer construction across Pasadena, Calabasas, and the Westside. Our techs see LG dryers every day, and the same handful of failures account for most service calls: <strong>vent blockage</strong> (LG's FlowSense system telegraphs this with D80/D90/D95 codes, most other brands stay silent until the thermal fuse blows), <strong>heating element burnout</strong> (year 8-12 typical with normal vent maintenance), <strong>squeaking idler pulley + drum belt</strong> (year 5-9), and the <strong>tE / HE / dE error codes</strong> that point at thermistor, heating circuit, or door faults respectively.</p>

    <p>One LG-specific service strength shapes how we approach diagnostics: <strong>FlowSense vent-restriction sensing</strong>. LG dryers measure airflow obstruction by tracking how quickly the high-limit thermostat operates relative to when the heater turns on, and the control board converts that timing into the D-series vent-blockage codes. D80 = 80-90% blocked, D90 = 90%+ blocked, D95 = severe. Other major dryer brands tend to stay silent on partial vent restriction until something fails, LG telegraphs the problem before damage cascades. About 70% of D-series codes resolve at vent cleaning alone with no parts replacement; the remaining 30% reveal a secondary issue that the restriction was masking.</p>

    <p>This page covers LG dryer repair across all major DLE, DLEX, DLG, and WashTower model families. Every service call gets a $89 residential diagnostic (applied toward the repair when work is approved), OEM parts where we can, and an honest written quote before any work begins.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 COMMON PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Common LG dryer problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What goes wrong on LG dryers, and how we diagnose it.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Six problem categories account for most LG dryer service calls. Each has a typical year-window and a diagnostic order that gets to root cause efficiently.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Not heating (the #1 call)</h3>
        <p>Diagnostic order: vent inspection first (LG's FlowSense should already be telegraphing D80/D90/D95 if blockage is severe; partial blockage outside FlowSense detection range still drives HE), heating element resistance test, thermistor read, gas valve coil test on DLG. About 50% of no-heat calls trace to vent + thermal fuse; 30% to heating element burnout; 15% to thermistor or thermostat; 5% to control board.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>D80 / D90 / D95 vent codes</h3>
        <p>FlowSense detection of progressive vent blockage. D80 = mild (still drying, just slowly). D90 = severe (cycle terminations starting). D95 = critical (dryer refusing to run normally). Full vent inspection and cleaning resolves 70% at no parts cost. Remaining 30% reveal failing FlowSense thermistor or thermal-cutoff fuse on edge of failure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Squeaking or grinding noise</h3>
        <p>Idler pulley bearing wear (high squeak, year 5-9) accounts for ~70% of noise calls. Drum support roller wear (rumble or grind, year 7-11) accounts for ~25%. Drive motor bearing failure is the remaining ~5%, distinguished by listening through a stethoscope or manually rotating the drum with belt removed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Won't start or won't tumble</h3>
        <p>Door switch / door latch fault (year 3-7 typical, dE error code if displayed), drive belt broken (motor runs but drum doesn't turn, year 8-12), drive motor failure (no motor sound at all, year 10+), main control board (no power-on response, diagnose via multimeter at incoming power leg).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Won't stop / runs continuously</h3>
        <p>Moisture sensor coated with dryer-sheet wax is the most common cause, sensor reads "wet" continuously and dryer keeps running. Cleaning the sensor strip (standard inside-drum clean with rubbing alcohol) is a 10-minute, no-parts fix on ~60% of these calls. Less common: timer or control board sensing fault.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>TurboSteam not generating steam</h3>
        <p>DLEX TurboSteam variants add a steam generator to the failure tree. Symptoms: no steam during steam cycles, water pooling in the bottom of the drum, or SE error variant. Diagnostic: water inlet valve, steam generator element, steam line. Replacement runs $245-$385 depending on which steam component failed.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 ERROR CODES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03, LG dryer error codes decoded</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What the codes on your LG dryer actually mean.</h2>

    <p>LG's dryer error codes are some of the most informative in the industry, when displayed and interpreted correctly, they cut diagnostic time substantially. The common ones we translate on every service visit:</p>

    <div class="error-table">
      <div class="error-row"><strong>D80</strong>, Vent 80-90% blocked. Full vent inspection and cleaning. 70% resolve at this step.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>D90</strong>, Vent 90%+ blocked. Same diagnostic; more cycle terminations.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>D95</strong>, Critical vent blockage. Dryer refusing to run normally.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>tE / tE1 / tE4</strong>, Thermistor fault. Sensor, harness, or board.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>tE2</strong>, Air thermistor fault (intake or outlet temperature sensor).</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>HE</strong>, Heating circuit error. Element, fuse, gas coils, or wiring.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>dE</strong>, Door not latched. Latch, switch, or harness.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F</strong>, General fault flag. Look for accompanying code.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>nP</strong>, No power supply detected. Outlet wiring or breaker.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>FE</strong>, Frequency error (rare). Power supply or board.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>EE</strong>, EEPROM error on control board. Board replacement usually needed.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>OE</strong>, Drain error (steam-equipped models). Drain pump or hose.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>PS</strong>, Power surge protection (some models). Reset and monitor.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>CL</strong>, Child lock active (informational, not a fault).</div>
    </div>

    <p>Reset procedure for any LG dryer error code: kill the breaker for a full 10 minutes (longer than most appliances need, LG control boards have larger filter capacitors than most competitors). About 10-15% of error codes clear at this step at no parts cost, a transient fault the board latched. If the code returns, that's the diagnostic.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 MODELS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, LG dryer models we service most often</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">DLE, DLEX, DLG, and WashTower model families.</h2>

    <p class="lead">A representative sample of LG dryer model families our techs service routinely. Not exhaustive, LG's catalog is broad, but covers the units that show up most often on our route.</p>

    <div class="model-grid">
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>DLE-Standard Electric</h3>
        <p class="model-list">DLE7300WE · DLE7100W · DLE7000W · DLE3500W · DLE3400W</p>
        <p>The bread-and-butter LG electric dryer family. Standard 240V install. Vent + thermal fuse failures dominate service mix.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>DLEX Premium Electric (TurboSteam)</h3>
        <p class="model-list">DLEX7800WE · DLEX9000V · DLEX7900VE · DLEX4500W · DLEX3700W</p>
        <p>Premium DLEX-series with TurboSteam, smart features, and larger 7.4 cu ft capacity. Higher parts cost on premium boards and steam generators; same fundamental dryer service tree.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>DLG-Series Gas Dryers</h3>
        <p class="model-list">DLG7301WE · DLG7401WE · DLG3501W · DLG3601W · DLG7101W</p>
        <p>Gas dryer variants of the DLE electric family. Same chassis, gas valve assembly + igniter + flame sensor replace the electric heating element. Gas valve coil failures cluster year 9-12.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>WashTower Vertical Stack</h3>
        <p class="model-list">WKEX200HWA · WKE100HVA · WKHC202HBA · WKGX201HBA</p>
        <p>Single-chassis stacked washer + dryer combination. Same dryer diagnostic tree as separate DLE-series, tighter service access, often requires pulling the unit forward for major work.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>SteamFresh / Steam-equipped variants</h3>
        <p class="model-list">DLEX7900VE · DLEX9000V · DLGX7901WE · DLGX9001V</p>
        <p>SteamFresh dryers add a steam generator to the failure tree. Water inlet valve, steam element, and steam line are the additional service items year 7+.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Older / Legacy DLE-series</h3>
        <p class="model-list">DLE7177WM · DLE2240W · DLE5955W · DLE0442W · DLE0452W</p>
        <p>Pre-2018 DLE models still in heavy service. Standard electric dryer service tree applies. Year 10+ on these starts crossing the repair-vs-replace threshold for major work.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 REPAIR VS REPLACE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05, Repair vs replace</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">When an LG dryer is worth fixing, and when it isn't.</h2>

    <p>LG dryers should run reliably to year 12-15 with normal vent maintenance and the typical thermal-fuse + element + belt service items handled along the way. Repair-vs-replace economics work as a function of dryer age and repair cost:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Under year 6:</strong> Repair almost always. Even the bigger-ticket repairs (drive motor, control board) buy 6-9 more years of service.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 6-10:</strong> Repair for any quote under $400, that's most calls. The thermal fuse / vent / heating element / belt + idler / door switch repairs land in the $145-$425 range and are no-brainers in this window.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 10-12:</strong> Repair-vs-replace turns case-by-case. Repairs under $300 still make sense. Repairs over $400, especially drive motor, control board, or multiple components on the same call, start tilting toward replacement, especially on entry-tier DLE2 series.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 12+:</strong> Replacement is usually right unless you have a high-spec WashTower or TurboSteam DLEX where the replacement cost is substantial enough to justify a major repair on the existing unit.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The 50% rule of thumb: <strong>if the repair quote exceeds 50% of replacement cost AND the unit is over 10 years old, replacement usually wins</strong>. Our techs do the math out loud on the diagnostic visit and tell you which call we'd make. We don't profit from talking customers into repairs that don't make sense, the right answer is sometimes "buy a new one," and we say so.</p>
  </div>
</section>

